{"answer":"From a public health perspective, the evidence directly addressing how intermittent fasting (IF) benefits and risks vary across socioeconomic strata, or its integration into SNAP/WIC, is sparse and indirect. The umbrella review by Patikorn et al. [Sources 1, 2, 8] indicates IF may yield beneficial effects across a range of health outcomes for adults with overweight or obesity compared to caloric restriction, and a JACC meta-analysis [Source 3] reports slightly greater weight loss and waist-circumference reduction versus continuous restriction, with improvements in fasting glucose. Source 6 confirms IF lowers total cholesterol, LDL, body weight and BMI. Risks include mild nausea, dizziness, feeling cold, and constipation in 2-7% of participants [Source 4], and one 19,000-adult study linked eight-hour eating windows to higher cardiovascular mortality [Source 7].

Regarding socioeconomic stratification, Source 5 profiles IF prevalence among Spanish citizens but does not examine US income gradients. Pureza et al. [Source 11] provide the most direct low-income evidence, assessing long-term time-restricted feeding in low-income women with obesity. Source 10 establishes that socioeconomic status, education, income, and occupation are major social determinants shaping diet-related disease outcomes, implying feasibility would differ across strata, though it does not evaluate IF specifically.

Crucially, no source evaluates IF delivered through SNAP or WIC. The available federal-nutrition-program trials test Food-is-Medicine and food-insecurity interventions [Sources 12, 14, 15], such as Packed Promise and Ticket to Healthy Food, which target food insecurity reduction rather than fasting protocols. Source 14 notes medically tailored groceries serve low-income populations with diet-related chronic conditions. Evidence gap: no RCTs examine IF safety, adherence, or equity outcomes within SNAP/WIC; feasibility claims would be speculative given food-insecurity constraints these programs address.","key_findings":["IF produces modest weight, lipid, and glycemic benefits versus continuous caloric restriction in adults with overweight/obesity [Sources 1, 2, 3, 6, 8].","Documented risks include mild nausea, dizziness, constipation (2-7%) and a signal of elevated cardiovascular mortality with 8-hour eating windows [Sources 4, 7].","Only one study directly examines IF in low-income populations (time-restricted feeding in low-income women with obesity) [Source 11].","Socioeconomic status is an established social determinant of diet-related disease, but no reviewed source stratifies IF outcomes by income, education, or occupation in the US [Source 10].","No evidence exists on IF implementation, feasibility, or safety within SNAP or WIC; federal nutrition program RCTs address food insecurity, not fasting protocols [Sources 12, 14, 15]."],"sources_used":["https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38500840/","https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10945168/","https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/S0735-1097%2825%2901455-X","https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12916-024-03716-1","https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/16/13/2028","https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12309044/","https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c0l6ye6xe12o","https://www.researchgate.net/publication/379077659_Intermittent_fasting_and_health_outcomes_an_umbrella_review_of_systematic_reviews_and_meta-analyses_of_randomised_controlled_trials","https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32713721/","https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2212267220305426","https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIR.0000000000001343","https://www.jandonline.org/article/S2212-2672(20)30968-0/pdf","https://diabetesjournals.org/care/article/44/1/258/33180/Social-Determinants-of-Health-and-Diabetes-A"]}
